Kramers rate theory

guillefix 26th March 2016 at 4:34am

Laplace method approximation of the mean first-passage time for a degree of freedom following a Fokker-Planck equation to overcome a barrier. Most easily solved in 1D, where the result is:

which is known as Kramers escape time. The exponential has the same form as the phenomenological Arrhenius equation, and the pre-factor is known as the inverse attempt frequency.

It is used to estimate reaction rates in Chemical kinetics where one defines a reaction coordinate approximating the evolution of the relevant molecules and their potential energy.

Barrier crossover time from probability distribution

Can use the (conditional) probability distribution P(x,t∣x0,t0)P(x,t|x_0,t_0)P(x,t∣x​0​​,t​0​​) when a barrier is present to calculate the crossover time. This is done by considering the flux JJJ (see Fokker-Planck equation). The probability distribution for crossing the barrier is then:

P(t)=J(Δx,t∣−Δx,t0)∫0∞dtJ(Δx,t∣−Δx,t0)P(t) = \frac{J(\Delta x, t| - \Delta x, t_0)}{\int_0^\infty dt J(\Delta x, t| - \Delta x, t_0)}P(t)=​∫​0​∞​​dtJ(Δx,t∣−Δx,t​0​​)​​J(Δx,t∣−Δx,t​0​​)​​

where we assume the barrier is at 000, so that −Δx- \Delta x−Δx and Δx\Delta xΔx are at opposite sides.

The probability distribution for crossing the barrier above, is the same as the probability distribution for the first passage time. To understand why we use the flux (current, JJJ) to calculate this, imagine many instances of the Brownian particle in the potential. We can approximate the above P(t)P(t)P(t) by just considering frequencies, in the limit of infinite instances. Now, JJJ is just calculated by counting the number of times a particle is found within dxdxdx of the point Δx\Delta xΔx, at time ttt, multiplied by its velocity at that moment.
